descript.abstract: Red channel grid of the U.S. Gulf Coast derived from 30-meter National Elevation Dataset (NED) data which was resampled down to 500 meters. When combined with the corresponding green and blue grids into a multi-band dataset or grid stack, these datasets depict a color shaded relief representation of the region, in which the first 30 feet of relief above mean sea level are displayed as brightly colored 5-foot elevation bands (refer to legend file "colorkey_elevmap_gulf_inset.jpg"). This data is designed to support U.S. Geological Survey (USGS) disaster preparedness efforts and is meant to be used at a broad scale and for informational purposes only.

procstep.procdesc: The NED data was derived from the original 1:24,000-scale USGS topographic map bare-earth contours, which were converted into gridded quadrangle-based DEM tiles at a constant post spacing (grid cell size) of either 30 meters (circa pre-1990s data) or 10 meters (circa 1990s and later data). These individual-quadrangle DEMs were then converted to spherical coordinates (latitude/longitude decimal degrees) and edge-matched to ensure seamlessness. The NED source data for this dataset consists of a mixture of 30-meter- and 10-meter-resolution DEMs.
The NED data was downloaded from http://seamless.usgs.gov circa 2004 or 2005. This data was then projected into Albers Equal Area NAD83 at 30-meter horizontal resolution.
The 30-meter UTM elevation grid was resampled to 500-meter resolution.
The 500-meter elevation grid was SLICEd into elevation color ranges using a remap table and a color file.
